WEBVTT

00:01.418 --> 00:02.920
NARRATOR:
Previously on
When Calls the Heart:

00:02.920 --> 00:04.880
I'm offering you
a division of your own.

00:04.880 --> 00:06.214
I'm honored,
but I have a job.

00:06.214 --> 00:07.591
Would you take the railroad

00:07.591 --> 00:09.050
as one of your clients?
It's a deal.

00:09.050 --> 00:10.928
Rosemary, you've worked
at this cafe before.

00:10.928 --> 00:12.387
We're gonna need
some help here.

00:12.387 --> 00:13.514
I'll take the job.

00:13.514 --> 00:15.056
Hope Valley
wants this railroad,

00:15.056 --> 00:16.183
but not at any price.

00:16.183 --> 00:17.434
I vote against the railroad's

00:17.434 --> 00:18.644
current proposal.

00:19.311 --> 00:21.814
[♪♪♪]

00:23.231 --> 00:24.942
FRANK:
You made the right decision.

00:24.942 --> 00:26.694
ABIGAIL:
Half the town
agrees with you.

00:26.694 --> 00:28.069
The other half's
just afraid

00:28.069 --> 00:29.112
to lose
the railroad.

00:29.112 --> 00:30.405
And with good reason.

00:30.405 --> 00:31.866
Listen, Abigail,
I'm your friend,

00:31.866 --> 00:33.033
you know that, but...

00:33.033 --> 00:34.409
You think
I'm making a mistake.

00:34.409 --> 00:36.244
Bringing the railroad
to Hope Valley

00:36.244 --> 00:38.205
benefits everybody
in the long run.

00:38.205 --> 00:40.833
If Jed and a few farmers
have to move,

00:40.833 --> 00:43.126
maybe that's the price
we pay for progress.

00:43.126 --> 00:44.252
That's the price
they pay.

00:44.252 --> 00:45.420
You're making profits.

00:45.420 --> 00:47.214
And putting
a lot of people to work.

00:47.214 --> 00:49.008
What about their homes
and their families?

00:49.008 --> 00:50.592
Gentlemen, we all want
what's best

00:50.592 --> 00:51.886
for Hope Valley.

00:51.886 --> 00:53.595
Let's just hope we get it.

00:55.931 --> 00:57.766
ABIGAIL:
Mr. Wyatt.

00:59.059 --> 01:00.686
May I have a word?

01:00.686 --> 01:02.312
Of course.

01:05.106 --> 01:06.692
ABIGAIL:
Thank you.

01:07.651 --> 01:08.736
I've been thinking about

01:08.736 --> 01:10.779
the town meeting,
Mr. Wyatt.

01:10.779 --> 01:12.155
Ready to change
your mind?

01:12.155 --> 01:13.824
Not exactly.

01:13.824 --> 01:15.993
Well, then I'm not sure
there's much to talk about,

01:15.993 --> 01:17.036
so if you'll excuse me.

01:17.036 --> 01:18.161
I think we can make a deal,

01:18.161 --> 01:19.454
if we both
compromise a little.

01:19.454 --> 01:20.873
Unless you're willing
to sell me

01:20.873 --> 01:22.041
the land to the south--

01:22.041 --> 01:23.042
Please, just listen.

01:23.042 --> 01:24.251
I know that moving the route

01:24.251 --> 01:25.794
will cost the railroad
more money.

01:25.794 --> 01:27.128
But I can help.

01:27.128 --> 01:29.088
And just how do you
propose to do that?

01:29.965 --> 01:31.132
I propose to sell you

01:31.132 --> 01:33.427
the parcel along
the northern route

01:33.427 --> 01:34.595
at half-price.

01:34.595 --> 01:36.513
The land is vacant,

01:36.513 --> 01:38.557
so you won't have to pay
to relocate anyone.

01:39.808 --> 01:41.685
It's a good compromise,
Mr. Wyatt,

01:41.685 --> 01:43.520
and we both know it.

01:44.855 --> 01:47.106
I'll consider it
and I'll get back to you.

01:48.442 --> 01:50.235
You'll get back to me now.

01:50.235 --> 01:52.112
The railroad is
good for business here,

01:52.112 --> 01:54.782
which is the only reason
I'm willing to negotiate...

01:54.782 --> 01:57.409
but we can get along
just fine without you.

01:57.409 --> 02:00.412
My offer expires
when I walk out the door.

02:00.412 --> 02:02.664
I don't like
to rush big decisions.

02:02.664 --> 02:05.417
Mr. Wyatt, we both know
the National Pacific

02:05.417 --> 02:07.419
wants to run the main line
through Hope Valley

02:07.419 --> 02:09.797
because it's the most direct
route to the coast.

02:09.797 --> 02:11.632
But I'm sure
they'll understand

02:11.632 --> 02:13.968
why you didn't
want to be rushed.

02:18.179 --> 02:19.807
I accept your offer.

02:23.852 --> 02:25.729
You drive a hard bargain.

02:25.729 --> 02:28.398
I'd say
it's a fair bargain.

02:28.398 --> 02:30.859
Good day, Mr. Wyatt.

02:30.859 --> 02:32.527
Just one more thing.

02:35.572 --> 02:37.950
[♪♪♪]

02:56.175 --> 02:59.138
[♪♪♪]

03:02.683 --> 03:04.225
ELIZABETH:
"The women of Hope Valley

03:04.225 --> 03:06.478
"never shy away
from a challenge.

03:06.478 --> 03:07.980
"Abigail Stanton might never

03:07.980 --> 03:09.773
"have intended
to serve as mayor,

03:09.773 --> 03:12.442
"but she rose to the occasion
and made a deal

03:12.442 --> 03:14.319
"with the National Pacific
Railroad

03:14.319 --> 03:17.031
"to bring us progress
and prosperity.

03:18.949 --> 03:22.285
"With both the railroad
and the sawmill hiring workers,

03:22.285 --> 03:25.288
"new faces are already
showing up in town,

03:25.288 --> 03:28.167
and in my classroom as well."

03:28.167 --> 03:30.961
[STUDENTS CHATTING INDISTINCTLY]

03:30.961 --> 03:33.005
[PLAYING SIMPLE TUNE]

03:34.173 --> 03:36.299
All right, everyone.
Settle down.

03:36.299 --> 03:37.384
Timmy...

03:37.384 --> 03:40.137
You can play piano at recess.

03:40.137 --> 03:41.596
Now, as you can see,

03:41.596 --> 03:43.598
we have a lot of new students
here today,

03:43.598 --> 03:46.518
so you will have to share
your books with a partner.

03:49.063 --> 03:51.481
Oh. Uh, Cody...

03:51.481 --> 03:53.067
Would you please pass these out?

03:53.067 --> 03:54.609
Thank you.

03:54.609 --> 03:55.819
[SIGHS]

03:55.819 --> 03:57.237
Good morning.

03:57.237 --> 03:59.114
They told me
this was the school.

03:59.114 --> 04:01.408
And I'm the teacher,
Elizabeth Thatcher.

04:01.408 --> 04:02.826
Shane Cantrell.

04:02.826 --> 04:04.786
This is my son, Philip.

04:04.786 --> 04:06.038
It's nice
to meet you, Philip.

04:06.038 --> 04:08.082
He hasn't done
much schooling,

04:08.082 --> 04:09.332
but he went to class

04:09.332 --> 04:11.334
for a few months
back in Rock Ridge.

04:11.334 --> 04:13.045
Well, that's a start.

04:13.045 --> 04:14.671
I'm gone all day at work,

04:14.671 --> 04:16.965
and he doesn't have a mother
to look after him.

04:16.965 --> 04:18.592
I'm so sorry to hear that.

04:18.592 --> 04:21.095
He knows most his letters,

04:21.095 --> 04:22.679
and he can add
and subtract a little.

04:22.679 --> 04:24.431
I'm sure he'll do just fine,

04:24.431 --> 04:27.101
and we would be delighted
to have you join us, Philip.

04:29.144 --> 04:30.938
You do as Teacher says,
you hear me?

04:30.938 --> 04:32.439
Yes, sir.

04:32.439 --> 04:34.566
Thank you, Miss...?

04:34.566 --> 04:35.567
Thatcher.

04:35.567 --> 04:37.444
Thatcher.

04:39.613 --> 04:41.573
Let's find you
a place to sit.

04:43.658 --> 04:45.285
It's okay.

04:47.328 --> 04:48.789
[DOOR CLOSES]

04:49.539 --> 04:51.917
[♪♪♪]

04:53.877 --> 04:56.630
How about
right here, next to Opal?

04:56.630 --> 04:58.465
And she can be
your reading partner.

04:58.465 --> 04:59.716
Yes, ma'am.

05:07.141 --> 05:08.976
Do you want
to know a secret?

05:08.976 --> 05:12.562
The first day of school
is hard for everyone.

05:12.562 --> 05:14.022
I'll be okay.

05:14.022 --> 05:15.356
I know you will.

05:21.155 --> 05:23.448
As soon as I think I've solved
one problem with Wyatt,

05:23.448 --> 05:24.908
he tosses me another.

05:24.908 --> 05:26.660
So they don't want
to pay any taxes at all?

05:26.660 --> 05:27.953
Zero,

05:27.953 --> 05:29.329
and I don't think
that's right.

05:29.329 --> 05:31.498
Well, from
what I've seen...

05:31.498 --> 05:34.293
"right" and "wrong" doesn't
matter to the railroad

05:34.293 --> 05:35.710
when it comes
to doing business.

05:35.710 --> 05:37.336
And yet,
you still work for them.

05:37.336 --> 05:39.840
Not everything
is always at it seems.

05:39.840 --> 05:42.092
Nothing with you ever is.

05:43.342 --> 05:44.552
Needs salt.

05:47.639 --> 05:49.390
[SIGHS]

05:52.853 --> 05:54.813
All right, everyone,
for your homework,

05:54.813 --> 05:56.190
I want you to read
the first chapter

05:56.190 --> 05:57.941
of Rebecca
Of Sunnybrook Farm.

05:57.941 --> 06:00.235
But there aren't enough
books to take home.

06:00.235 --> 06:02.361
And mine's
missing a page.

06:02.361 --> 06:03.362
I know.

06:03.362 --> 06:04.447
You'll have to take turns

06:04.447 --> 06:05.448
with your partners.

06:05.448 --> 06:06.533
So decide which one of you

06:06.533 --> 06:07.826
will take home the book tonight,

06:07.826 --> 06:09.661
and who will take it home
tomorrow night.

06:09.661 --> 06:11.246
Time for recess.

06:11.246 --> 06:12.956
[BELL RINGS]

06:12.956 --> 06:15.167
You can take
the book home first.

06:15.167 --> 06:17.211
I can't read all the words.

06:17.211 --> 06:19.754
Miss Thatcher says it's okay
to have your mommy help you.

06:19.754 --> 06:21.089
I don't have a mom.

06:21.089 --> 06:23.008
Then your dad
can read it to you.

06:23.008 --> 06:24.926
That's not what dads do.

06:24.926 --> 06:26.553
Mine does.

06:28.513 --> 06:31.099
[♪♪♪]

06:31.099 --> 06:33.352
Come on, Brownie.
I'll read to you.

06:38.606 --> 06:40.275
Could you bag up those scones
for Bill

06:40.275 --> 06:41.860
while I finish these eggs?

06:41.860 --> 06:43.778
[FIRE CRACKLING]

06:44.738 --> 06:45.947
Rosemary.

06:45.947 --> 06:47.199
Mm-hmm?

06:47.199 --> 06:48.449
Bill's waiting.

06:50.952 --> 06:53.663
Yes! Sorry. Right away.

06:53.663 --> 06:55.623
And then maybe
you can wash some dishes.

06:56.624 --> 06:57.709
Mm-hmm.

07:01.088 --> 07:03.131
With the railroad
coming to town,

07:03.131 --> 07:05.175
I figured now
was the perfect time.

07:05.175 --> 07:06.885
It is the perfect time.

07:06.885 --> 07:07.886
I hope so.

07:07.886 --> 07:09.388
I'm a little scared.

07:09.388 --> 07:10.555
Don't be scared.

07:10.555 --> 07:11.973
It's what
you've always wanted.

07:11.973 --> 07:13.308
You're doing
the right thing.

07:13.308 --> 07:14.393
Thank you.

07:14.393 --> 07:15.476
That means a lot.

07:15.476 --> 07:16.561
If it's okay with you,

07:16.561 --> 07:17.729
I would rather just
keep it

07:17.729 --> 07:19.356
[WHISPERS]
our little secret.

07:19.356 --> 07:20.565
You have my word.

07:23.318 --> 07:24.527
Did someone say "secret"?

07:24.527 --> 07:26.487
Oh! No, no, no.
We're just...

07:26.487 --> 07:27.822
just chatting, Rosemary.

07:27.822 --> 07:28.907
Thanks for these.

07:28.907 --> 07:30.242
Hmm.

07:32.244 --> 07:34.288
Dottie...
you have to tell me.

07:34.288 --> 07:36.164
Are you and Bill
officially courting again?

07:36.164 --> 07:38.208
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
No. We're just good friends.

07:38.208 --> 07:40.168
Oh, you poor dear.

07:40.168 --> 07:41.669
I'm so sorry.

07:41.669 --> 07:44.631
Rosemary, please.
It was a mutual decision.

07:45.799 --> 07:46.758
Oh.

07:46.758 --> 07:47.759
[CHUCKLES]

07:47.759 --> 07:49.219
Of course it was.

07:50.304 --> 07:51.679
So what's the secret?

07:53.640 --> 07:55.350
I will tell you,

07:55.350 --> 07:58.353
as long as you promise
not to mention it to anyone.

07:58.353 --> 08:01.648
I promise! I won't tell a soul.
My lips are sealed.

08:01.648 --> 08:03.650
I have decided...

08:05.110 --> 08:06.903
...to open a dress shop!
[GASPS]

08:06.903 --> 08:08.405
Dottie!

08:08.405 --> 08:10.282
That's a wonderful idea!

08:10.282 --> 08:13.701
Hope Valley desperately
needs some haute couture.

08:13.701 --> 08:15.412
Oh, you must tell me
all about it.

08:15.412 --> 08:17.164
CLARA:
Rosemary!

08:17.164 --> 08:19.291
Dishes! Now?

08:19.291 --> 08:20.625
Coming!

08:20.625 --> 08:23.503
Now... you were saying?

08:23.503 --> 08:26.298
[STUDENTS CHATTING INDISTINCTLY]

08:31.303 --> 08:33.347
Philip?

08:33.347 --> 08:35.223
Isn't there anyone here
to walk you home?

08:35.223 --> 08:37.142
No, but
I know the way.

08:37.142 --> 08:39.019
Well, maybe I could
walk with you.

08:39.019 --> 08:40.687
You don't have to.

08:40.687 --> 08:42.105
I would like to.

08:42.105 --> 08:43.315
Okay, but first,

08:43.315 --> 08:44.691
I have to stop
at the mercantile.

08:44.691 --> 08:46.567
My dad ordered
some things for us.

08:46.567 --> 08:47.944
What a coincidence.

08:47.944 --> 08:49.988
I also have to stop
at the mercantile.

08:49.988 --> 08:51.698
Do you think we could
walk together?

08:51.698 --> 08:53.992
I guess.
Hmm.

08:53.992 --> 08:56.661
Even with all the extra workers,
we're falling behind.

08:56.661 --> 08:57.745
We need more men.

08:57.745 --> 08:58.913
Don't I know it.

08:58.913 --> 09:00.499
Bad news, Mr. Coulter.
What now?

09:00.499 --> 09:02.292
The rip saw's
lost its treadle again.

09:02.292 --> 09:03.877
It's gonna take all day to fix.

09:03.877 --> 09:05.628
Plus, that main generator's
about to go.

09:05.628 --> 09:06.796
Of course it is.

09:06.796 --> 09:08.089
MURPHY:
All due respect, sir,

09:08.089 --> 09:09.549
Mr. Wyatt's expecting
his first

09:09.549 --> 09:11.592
lumber delivery
in nine days.

09:11.592 --> 09:13.136
The only way
we can make that

09:13.136 --> 09:15.138
is if the men
work more hours.

09:15.138 --> 09:17.516
But we've been working
three hours overtime as it is.

09:17.516 --> 09:19.851
I'm grateful for the work,
don't get me wrong--

09:19.851 --> 09:21.395
I know you are.

09:21.395 --> 09:22.645
I know you are...

09:22.645 --> 09:23.897
But Murphy's right.

09:23.897 --> 09:25.940
If this railroad
contract goes away,

09:25.940 --> 09:27.692
we're gonna lose
a lot of jobs with it.

09:28.860 --> 09:30.611
I don't see any other way.

09:30.611 --> 09:33.073
So...back to work.

09:33.073 --> 09:35.158
You too.
Yes, sir.

09:35.158 --> 09:36.284
Mm-hmm.

09:37.702 --> 09:39.996
[EXHALES,
MUTTERS INDISTINCTLY]

09:43.500 --> 09:45.919
Hey, Philip.
Want to play catch?

09:45.919 --> 09:47.087
What? Don't you
have homework?

09:47.087 --> 09:48.338
Nope.

09:48.338 --> 09:50.549
Miss Thatcher
always gives homework.

09:50.549 --> 09:52.675
Well, we had
a story to read,

09:52.675 --> 09:55.053
but tonight is Anna's turn
to take the book home.

09:55.053 --> 09:56.971
So can we play?

09:56.971 --> 09:58.390
I don't have a glove.

09:58.390 --> 09:59.516
You can use mine.

09:59.516 --> 10:00.767
We'll grab my bat.

10:00.767 --> 10:02.060
PHILIP:
Is it okay?

10:02.060 --> 10:03.144
Just ten minutes.

10:03.144 --> 10:04.521
Of course,
but then I think

10:04.521 --> 10:06.314
I should really walk you home.

10:06.314 --> 10:08.108
That is, as long as
it's all right

10:08.108 --> 10:09.401
with Miss Abigail?

10:09.401 --> 10:10.902
Go on. Have fun.

10:13.821 --> 10:15.949
Aren't there enough
readers to go around?

10:15.949 --> 10:18.701
No, and the ones we do have
are falling apart.

10:18.701 --> 10:20.036
With all
these new students,

10:20.036 --> 10:21.580
I'm going to need
more of everything.

10:21.580 --> 10:24.082
I wish I had
an easy answer for you.

10:24.082 --> 10:26.501
Well, there must be some room
in the town's budget

10:26.501 --> 10:27.919
for more
supplies for the school.

10:27.919 --> 10:29.170
Right now, you're gonna

10:29.170 --> 10:30.630
have to make do
with what you have.

10:30.630 --> 10:31.965
But Abigail,
this is important.

10:31.965 --> 10:33.967
I know, and I
would give the moon

10:33.967 --> 10:35.635
to those children
if I could,

10:35.635 --> 10:38.513
but there isn't enough
to go around right now.

10:38.513 --> 10:40.765
I guess these are just
growing pains, huh?

10:40.765 --> 10:42.725
Now the good news is,
they do go away.

10:42.725 --> 10:43.768
[DRY CHUCKLE]

10:43.768 --> 10:45.770
Eventually.
Heh, heh.

10:47.439 --> 10:48.815
[SIGHS]

10:51.192 --> 10:54.862
ROSEMARY:
Just a bit more shape, and...

10:54.862 --> 10:56.781
a bit more train...

10:56.781 --> 11:01.286
and a lot more décolletage.

11:01.286 --> 11:02.996
A lot more what?

11:02.996 --> 11:04.747
[CHUCKLES]

11:06.249 --> 11:08.876
Rosemary, where's the kettle?
I'd love some tea.

11:08.876 --> 11:11.087
Uh, yes, the kettle...

11:11.087 --> 11:12.671
Uh, oh, yes.

11:12.671 --> 11:14.591
Right there, heh.

11:14.591 --> 11:16.551
Looks like
we had a busy afternoon.

11:16.551 --> 11:19.053
Yes. Very busy. Uh...

11:19.053 --> 11:20.888
Really kept us hopping.

11:22.015 --> 11:24.142
Clara had offered to stay

11:24.142 --> 11:25.477
and help with the dishes,

11:25.477 --> 11:27.521
but she'd already
worked a full shift,

11:27.521 --> 11:29.564
so I told her not to worry,

11:29.564 --> 11:32.400
I would
take care of the rest.

11:32.400 --> 11:34.027
Thank you, Rosemary.

11:34.027 --> 11:36.196
I'm sorry Bill and I
haven't been here to pitch in.

11:36.196 --> 11:38.281
No apology needed.

11:38.281 --> 11:39.824
No, you both have
your hands full,

11:39.824 --> 11:41.242
and that's why you hired me.

11:41.242 --> 11:43.578
To help
in your time of need.

11:43.578 --> 11:45.997
I really appreciate it.

11:45.997 --> 11:49.834
And I'm gonna try
to find a clean tea cup.

11:49.834 --> 11:51.085
[CHUCKLES]

11:51.085 --> 11:52.837
[EXASPERATED SIGHS]

11:58.176 --> 12:01.012
ELIZABETH:
"...And the duck said,
'Quack, quack, quack.'"

12:01.012 --> 12:02.639
That's not how ducks sound.

12:02.639 --> 12:03.931
Oh? How do they sound?

12:03.931 --> 12:05.308
"Quack, quack, quack."

12:05.308 --> 12:06.976
Heh, heh.
All right, let me try.

12:06.976 --> 12:08.895
"Quack, quack, quack."

12:08.895 --> 12:10.938
[ELIZABETH LAUGHS]

12:10.938 --> 12:12.273
Miss Thatcher?

12:13.316 --> 12:14.817
Is there a problem?

12:14.817 --> 12:16.194
No, no problem at all.

12:16.194 --> 12:17.445
Philip had a great first day.

12:17.445 --> 12:18.821
You should be very proud.

12:18.821 --> 12:20.281
Then what are you doing here?

12:20.281 --> 12:21.740
I just thought
I'd walk him home.

12:21.740 --> 12:24.035
Oh. Well, thanks.

12:24.035 --> 12:26.663
But he can
take care of himself.

12:26.663 --> 12:29.290
Um, I spoke with
Mrs. Brayman,

12:29.290 --> 12:31.209
and since her daughter
is also in my class,

12:31.209 --> 12:33.670
she said she could walk Philip
home from school from now on.

12:33.670 --> 12:35.129
And she offered
to keep an eye on him

12:35.129 --> 12:36.423
while you're in
the sawmill.

12:36.423 --> 12:38.174
If that's
what she wants to do.

12:38.174 --> 12:41.386
Guess it's a woman's
nature to worry.

12:41.386 --> 12:43.054
We better go
scare up some supper.

12:43.054 --> 12:44.305
Yes, sir.

12:44.305 --> 12:45.724
I was wondering
if you and Philip

12:45.724 --> 12:47.141
might like to come over
to my house

12:47.141 --> 12:48.727
for dinner
sometime this week.

12:48.727 --> 12:50.853
I'm sure you both could
use a home-cooked meal.

12:50.853 --> 12:53.273
That's very kind,
but we wouldn't want to impose.

12:53.273 --> 12:54.899
No, I like to get
to know my students

12:54.899 --> 12:56.150
outside the classroom.

12:56.150 --> 12:57.818
It helps me
understand them better.

12:57.818 --> 12:58.945
Well, thanks just the same.

12:58.945 --> 13:00.113
Come on, now.

13:01.906 --> 13:04.284
Thanks for walking me home,
Miss Thatcher.

13:04.284 --> 13:05.910
You're welcome, Philip.

13:07.495 --> 13:09.456
[♪♪♪]

13:09.456 --> 13:10.498
[GASPS SOFTLY]

13:10.498 --> 13:11.790
Oh.

13:14.085 --> 13:15.295
I'll see you tomorrow.

13:26.306 --> 13:27.682
JACK:
Bill.

13:28.891 --> 13:31.018
I just got word
from Headquarters.

13:31.018 --> 13:33.647
The Tate Boys just broke out
of Granville Penitentiary.

13:33.647 --> 13:35.022
Granville?
That's up north.

13:35.022 --> 13:36.399
We think they're
headed our way.

13:36.399 --> 13:37.816
Criminal gangs
are fighting

13:37.816 --> 13:39.736
for control of
the Northern Territory.

13:39.736 --> 13:41.028
It's a lot
safer out here

13:41.028 --> 13:42.530
for bottom-feeders
like the Tates.

13:42.530 --> 13:44.449
Why bother with
a town small as this?

13:44.449 --> 13:46.242
Curtis and Glenn Tate
make their living

13:46.242 --> 13:47.702
robbing payrolls.

13:47.702 --> 13:49.746
And don't you have
a payroll coming in soon?

13:49.746 --> 13:51.581
Day after tomorrow.

13:51.581 --> 13:52.791
By coach, from Buxton.

13:52.791 --> 13:54.417
It's gonna
need protecting.

13:54.417 --> 13:55.627
Agreed.

13:55.627 --> 13:57.170
Bill and I
are gonna ride out

13:57.170 --> 13:59.547
and escort it back,
just in case.

13:59.547 --> 14:01.299
Any intel on
how the Tates operate?

14:01.299 --> 14:03.217
We could use
some inside information.

14:03.217 --> 14:05.595
I think I know
where to get it.

14:08.515 --> 14:11.058
[♪♪♪]

14:16.063 --> 14:17.774
Bon appétit.

14:20.067 --> 14:21.569
I asked for pancakes.

14:21.569 --> 14:24.155
Elizabeth,
you must expand your palate

14:24.155 --> 14:25.365
beyond such simple fare.

14:25.365 --> 14:27.074
I like my palate
just the way it is!

14:27.074 --> 14:29.243
Oh, did we wake up
on the wrong side

14:29.243 --> 14:30.286
of the bed this morning?

14:30.286 --> 14:32.121
I'm sorry. I'm just...

14:32.121 --> 14:34.248
I'm worried about
the school right now.

14:34.248 --> 14:35.500
Well, maybe I can help.

14:35.500 --> 14:37.126
Not unless you have
a barrel of money.

14:37.126 --> 14:38.169
We're short on books,

14:38.169 --> 14:39.212
we're short on supplies,

14:39.212 --> 14:40.421
we're short on everything.

14:40.421 --> 14:41.589
Well, Abigail's the mayor,

14:41.589 --> 14:42.674
and she's your friend.

14:42.674 --> 14:43.966
Just ask her
for what you need.

14:43.966 --> 14:45.719
There's nothing
she can do right now.

14:45.719 --> 14:46.886
Hmm.

14:46.886 --> 14:48.262
So your little
schoolhouse

14:48.262 --> 14:49.681
is short on funds,

14:49.681 --> 14:51.683
and you need to raise some...

14:51.683 --> 14:53.727
Well, that means
you need a fundraiser.

14:53.727 --> 14:55.603
That's not a bad idea.

14:55.603 --> 14:57.021
Oh, it's a wonderful idea.

14:57.021 --> 14:58.815
In fact, I have a thought.

14:58.815 --> 15:01.275
We could organize a ball...

15:01.275 --> 15:03.695
A grand,
glorious gala.

15:03.695 --> 15:05.613
Rosemary.
Men could be in tuxedos,

15:05.613 --> 15:07.948
women in ball gowns,
waltzing the night away--

15:07.948 --> 15:09.200
Rosemary.

15:09.200 --> 15:10.577
Or we could
have a casino night

15:10.577 --> 15:12.537
in the saloon,
with a roulette wheel,

15:12.537 --> 15:14.163
card tables, dice games--

15:14.163 --> 15:15.373
Rosemary!

15:15.373 --> 15:17.917
This is a fundraiser
for children.

15:17.917 --> 15:18.959
They don't gamble.

15:18.959 --> 15:20.294
Of course they don't.

15:20.294 --> 15:21.921
They could serve
the hors d'oeuvres.

15:21.921 --> 15:24.090
I know! I could put on a show
after dinner,

15:24.090 --> 15:25.675
like a supper club.

15:25.675 --> 15:27.510
What do you think
about a carnival?

15:27.510 --> 15:28.720
A carnival?

15:28.720 --> 15:29.763
Mm-hmm.

15:29.763 --> 15:30.889
Uh...

15:30.889 --> 15:32.265
Well, it's no supper club...

15:34.016 --> 15:35.309
But I think it could be fun.

15:35.309 --> 15:36.519
Thank you.

15:36.519 --> 15:37.687
You must have a raffle.

15:37.687 --> 15:39.647
Raffles bring in gobs of money.

15:39.647 --> 15:41.775
That could work,
but what would we raffle off?

15:41.775 --> 15:44.068
Well, I have
a beautiful hair comb

15:44.068 --> 15:46.905
from my Broadway debut
in The Hairdresser.

15:46.905 --> 15:47.906
Hmm?

15:47.906 --> 15:49.365
Rosemary.

15:49.365 --> 15:50.533
Shouldn't you be working?

15:50.533 --> 15:51.701
I am working.

15:51.701 --> 15:53.035
I'm helping Elizabeth
with her

15:53.035 --> 15:54.537
dear little carnival
for the school.

15:54.537 --> 15:55.830
A carnival?
Don't worry.

15:55.830 --> 15:57.164
It won't cost
the town a dime.

15:57.164 --> 15:58.165
We'll do everything with

15:58.165 --> 15:59.417
volunteers and donations.

15:59.417 --> 16:01.753
I could read
people's fortunes!

16:01.753 --> 16:03.797
I once played the role
of fortune teller

16:03.797 --> 16:05.298
in The Fortune Teller.

16:05.298 --> 16:07.717
Dreadful play,
but I got to keep the costume!

16:07.717 --> 16:09.135
[STIFLED LAUGH]
ABIGAIL: Rosemary,

16:09.135 --> 16:10.720
since you can see the future,

16:10.720 --> 16:13.097
can you see yourself washing
the dishes in the kitchen?

16:13.097 --> 16:14.390
I was letting them soak.

16:14.390 --> 16:15.725
They're soaked.

16:15.725 --> 16:17.310
[ROSEMARY SIGHS]

16:17.310 --> 16:18.895
Back to work, then.

16:20.563 --> 16:22.816
A carnival wouldn't
make the school a fortune,

16:22.816 --> 16:24.275
but it could tide us
over for a while.

16:24.275 --> 16:26.193
What do you think?
Let me know what you need.

16:26.193 --> 16:27.570
I'll help in any way I can.

16:27.570 --> 16:29.322
A carnival!

16:30.490 --> 16:32.283
EMILY:
That sounds like
so much fun!

16:32.283 --> 16:34.243
Brownie loves carnivals!

16:34.243 --> 16:35.745
Can we have
candy apples?

16:35.745 --> 16:37.330
We can have whatever we like.

16:37.330 --> 16:39.415
But first,
we have a lot to do.

16:39.415 --> 16:41.292
We have to paint signs,

16:41.292 --> 16:42.710
and hand out flyers,

16:42.710 --> 16:44.504
and make things
that we can sell.

16:44.504 --> 16:46.380
Miss Abigail
can help me make cupcakes

16:46.380 --> 16:47.924
for the bake sale booth.

16:47.924 --> 16:50.176
And I'll help!
I love cupcakes.

16:50.176 --> 16:51.678
My dad
can make the booths.

16:51.678 --> 16:53.304
And my mom can
sew the bean bags

16:53.304 --> 16:54.555
for the bean bag toss.

16:54.555 --> 16:55.598
That's great!

16:55.598 --> 16:57.099
We need all the help we can get.

16:57.099 --> 16:59.894
I have the sign-up sheets
right here.

17:02.021 --> 17:03.189
Here you go.

17:06.442 --> 17:09.069
Philip, aren't you excited?

17:09.069 --> 17:11.197
My daddy
won't be able to come

17:11.197 --> 17:13.741
'cause he has to work
at the sawmill.

17:13.741 --> 17:15.034
Mine too.

17:17.453 --> 17:19.455
Let me see
what I can do about that.

17:20.540 --> 17:21.791
FRANK:
My cell at Granville

17:21.791 --> 17:23.209
was right next
to Curtis Tate's.

17:23.209 --> 17:24.961
I met his brother
there, too.

17:24.961 --> 17:26.796
Anything you could tell us
that might help?

17:26.796 --> 17:28.673
Curtis did say, once,
that he had a good idea

17:28.673 --> 17:30.174
about robbing a stagecoach.

17:30.174 --> 17:31.968
It's good to know
he put his time in prison

17:31.968 --> 17:32.969
to good use.

17:32.969 --> 17:34.303
He said he'd hire

17:34.303 --> 17:35.847
a keen-eyed rifleman,
put him on a hill,

17:35.847 --> 17:37.390
and have him shoot
the wagon guards

17:37.390 --> 17:38.599
when they got close enough.

17:38.599 --> 17:39.809
Kill them in cold blood?

17:39.809 --> 17:42.311
Stupid and bloodthirsty
go together.

17:42.311 --> 17:44.104
The Tate brothers are cowards.

17:44.104 --> 17:45.565
They're not gonna make a move

17:45.565 --> 17:47.149
till the sniper's done his job.

17:47.149 --> 17:49.777
Sounds like we're gonna be
riding into an ambush.

17:49.777 --> 17:51.320
It's not
an ambush, Jack,

17:51.320 --> 17:52.572
if we know it's coming.

17:52.572 --> 17:54.032
And we'll know it's coming.

17:54.032 --> 17:55.115
We?

17:56.617 --> 17:57.911
I'll ride with you.

17:57.911 --> 17:59.662
Don't have to do that, Frank.

17:59.662 --> 18:01.956
Well, a lot of folks
are depending on that payroll.

18:01.956 --> 18:03.958
I'd like to help out.

18:03.958 --> 18:06.961
Unless you don't
want the company.

18:12.258 --> 18:13.843
All right.

18:13.843 --> 18:15.678
We leave at dawn.

18:17.346 --> 18:20.433
DOTTIE:
Rosemary, I'd like
some Jasmine tea, please?

18:20.433 --> 18:22.060
Coming right up.

18:22.060 --> 18:23.770
Oh. What are these?

18:23.770 --> 18:26.981
Sketches.
Well, dress designs.

18:26.981 --> 18:28.816
I see...

18:28.816 --> 18:30.150
They're just the ticket
to put

18:30.150 --> 18:31.527
your new shop on the map.

18:31.527 --> 18:33.071
Well, I haven't even
opened it yet.

18:33.071 --> 18:34.321
Never too soon to plan,

18:34.321 --> 18:37.033
and every fine dress shop
needs...

18:37.033 --> 18:39.077
A fine designer.

18:40.828 --> 18:42.663
Well...

18:42.663 --> 18:44.665
Aren't they...

18:46.042 --> 18:47.085
Ooh!

18:47.085 --> 18:49.169
Interesting.

18:49.169 --> 18:51.756
Is that all
you're going to say?

18:51.756 --> 18:54.300
They are a little...

18:54.300 --> 18:55.802
Hmm,

18:55.802 --> 18:57.887
extravagant for Hope Valley,
don't you think?

18:57.887 --> 19:01.432
So much chiffon,
and beading, and...

19:01.432 --> 19:02.934
These necklines--

19:02.934 --> 19:04.978
Too daring?
To put it mildly.

19:06.520 --> 19:08.022
Perhaps you're right.

19:09.440 --> 19:12.735
Our ladies aren't quite
ready for high fashion.

19:12.735 --> 19:14.320
At least not this high.

19:14.320 --> 19:16.155
Or low, as the case may be.

19:17.824 --> 19:19.075
[PAPERS RUSTLE]

19:19.075 --> 19:20.994
Thank you for your notes,
Dottie.

19:20.994 --> 19:23.370
My next attempt will be
much more to your liking.

19:23.370 --> 19:24.872
Oh, I didn't ask for...

19:24.872 --> 19:26.082
another attempt.

19:26.082 --> 19:27.207
[SIGHS]

19:27.207 --> 19:28.375
Oh, boy.

19:30.128 --> 19:32.212
Your men have been
working so hard.

19:32.212 --> 19:33.631
They need some rest.

19:33.631 --> 19:35.257
They need
to spend some time

19:35.257 --> 19:36.550
with their families.

19:36.550 --> 19:38.052
I want to say yes,
Elizabeth,

19:38.052 --> 19:39.219
but I just, I can't.

19:39.219 --> 19:40.638
Lee, it's just
one afternoon.

19:40.638 --> 19:42.849
If I miss
the delivery schedule

19:42.849 --> 19:44.391
and lose the railroad
contract,

19:44.391 --> 19:46.477
I'm gonna have
to lay people off.

19:46.477 --> 19:48.312
Do you want those
families to go hungry?

19:48.312 --> 19:49.396
Of course not!

19:49.396 --> 19:50.481
Look, Wyatt's already

19:50.481 --> 19:51.774
taking a risk on me as it is.

19:51.774 --> 19:53.526
He could've easily
shipped his lumber in

19:53.526 --> 19:55.153
from Union City,
but he didn't.

19:55.153 --> 19:56.988
I can't let him down.

19:56.988 --> 19:58.447
I'm sorry.

20:02.076 --> 20:03.494
[SIGHS]

20:07.414 --> 20:10.001
[♪♪♪]

20:12.378 --> 20:13.921
Excuse me, Abigail?

20:15.422 --> 20:18.551
I heard the railroad
won't be paying any taxes.

20:18.551 --> 20:19.635
Is that true?

20:19.635 --> 20:21.428
Nothing has
been decided yet.

20:21.428 --> 20:22.972
Doesn't seem fair
for the railroad

20:22.972 --> 20:24.264
to be the only
business in town

20:24.264 --> 20:25.641
not paying its share.
I agree,

20:25.641 --> 20:27.143
but it's not
quite that simple.

20:27.143 --> 20:28.394
It is for me.

20:28.394 --> 20:30.063
I mean, the railroad
should pay taxes

20:30.063 --> 20:32.106
like the rest of us,
that's all there is to it.

20:32.106 --> 20:33.273
[SIGHS]

20:33.273 --> 20:34.608
I-I can't help thinking

20:34.608 --> 20:36.402
that Mr. Gowen
would've had enough nerve

20:36.402 --> 20:37.737
to stand up to them.

20:37.737 --> 20:39.488
Ned, I recall you being

20:39.488 --> 20:41.032
a vocal supporter
of the railroad

20:41.032 --> 20:42.616
when it was put to a vote.

20:42.616 --> 20:44.035
And as for Mr. Gowen,

20:44.035 --> 20:45.786
he isn't your mayor anymore.

20:45.786 --> 20:46.829
I am.

20:46.829 --> 20:48.206
Well, then why aren't you

20:48.206 --> 20:49.498
protecting my interests?

20:49.498 --> 20:50.708
I'm trying to protect

20:50.708 --> 20:52.543
everyone's interests, Ned.

20:57.131 --> 20:58.925
[SIGHS]
Oh, Abigail!

20:58.925 --> 21:00.218
Thank heavens you're here.

21:00.218 --> 21:01.468
Is there a problem?

21:01.468 --> 21:03.012
I ordered
a simple cucumber sandwich

21:03.012 --> 21:04.430
and Rosemary
brought me this,

21:04.430 --> 21:06.432
with olives and tomato and...

21:06.432 --> 21:10.603
some kind of
inappropriate mustard.

21:12.063 --> 21:13.647
I'll take care of it.

21:13.647 --> 21:15.191
I don't know how on earth

21:15.191 --> 21:16.650
I was
supposed to eat that.

21:19.319 --> 21:21.030
ABIGAIL:
What on earth...?

21:21.030 --> 21:23.074
Miss Rosemary's
helping us make cupcakes

21:23.074 --> 21:24.408
for the carnival
bake sale.

21:24.408 --> 21:26.911
But not plain
old, boring cupcakes.

21:26.911 --> 21:28.746
These ones have
marzipan in 'em.

21:28.746 --> 21:31.749
And jelly and walnuts
and cheese too.

21:31.749 --> 21:32.959
[CHUCKLES]

21:32.959 --> 21:34.627
Boys, why don't you
go outside

21:34.627 --> 21:36.545
and play for a bit,
and I'll help Miss Rosemary

21:36.545 --> 21:37.546
clean up in here?

21:37.546 --> 21:39.590
Thanks!
Come on, Robert.

21:41.968 --> 21:44.011
Rosemary,
what's going on?

21:44.011 --> 21:45.679
Well, I was just
helping the boys

21:45.679 --> 21:47.723
with their little
carnival cupcakes.

21:47.723 --> 21:48.724
And this?

21:48.724 --> 21:50.768
Oh, isn't it a work of art?

21:50.768 --> 21:52.812
Rosemary,
this isn't a cucumber sandwich.

21:52.812 --> 21:54.563
There's cucumber
in there!

21:54.563 --> 21:56.356
Look under
the anchovy paste.

21:56.356 --> 21:58.151
Florence doesn't want
anchovy paste.

21:58.151 --> 21:59.443
She wants what she ordered.

21:59.443 --> 22:00.945
Oh, that is just so...

22:02.280 --> 22:05.032
Oh, dear.
You're angry with me.

22:05.032 --> 22:06.366
[SIGHS]

22:06.366 --> 22:08.452
I'm not angry.

22:08.452 --> 22:10.288
I...

22:11.455 --> 22:12.915
I understand.

22:12.915 --> 22:14.667
You do?

22:14.667 --> 22:16.585
Oh, what a relief.

22:16.585 --> 22:18.129
When I started to work here,

22:18.129 --> 22:20.131
I was so grateful
to have something to do,

22:20.131 --> 22:22.258
because Lee
was busy working.

22:22.258 --> 22:24.468
But this isn't me, Abigail.

22:24.468 --> 22:27.847
When I hear of Dottie
opening up a dress shop--

22:27.847 --> 22:30.641
You don't want to quit
because I'm relying on you.

22:30.641 --> 22:32.018
You're my friend.

22:32.018 --> 22:33.351
I can't let you down.

22:33.351 --> 22:34.937
You're my friend too,

22:34.937 --> 22:36.647
and I can't let you
be unhappy.

22:36.647 --> 22:39.357
Clara and I
will be fine.

22:39.357 --> 22:41.902
I'll put a "help wanted" sign
in the window today.

22:41.902 --> 22:43.237
Are you sure?

22:43.237 --> 22:45.072
Rosemary, I think we both know

22:45.072 --> 22:47.074
you are not cut out
to do dishes.

22:47.074 --> 22:48.784
[BOTH LAUGH]

22:48.784 --> 22:51.329
Well, the least I can do
is fix this sandwich.

22:51.329 --> 22:52.330
Mmm!

22:52.330 --> 22:53.413
[CHUCKLES]

22:53.413 --> 22:54.498
Oh...

22:55.541 --> 22:57.501
Oh, my kitchen...

22:58.961 --> 23:00.378
[SIGHS]

23:00.378 --> 23:01.922
I'm riding out
at dawn.

23:01.922 --> 23:03.841
I should be back
by nightfall.

23:03.841 --> 23:05.968
I don't like
that word "should."

23:07.427 --> 23:10.264
I will be back by nightfall.

23:10.264 --> 23:11.974
I'm going to hold you to it.

23:11.974 --> 23:13.559
We don't even know
if the Tate boys

23:13.559 --> 23:15.477
are anywhere
near Hope Valley.

23:15.477 --> 23:17.897
We're just riding along
to be on the safe side.

23:17.897 --> 23:19.982
You are just trying
to make me feel better.

23:19.982 --> 23:21.234
Is it working?

23:25.571 --> 23:27.907
Let me try something else.

23:33.913 --> 23:36.374
[♪♪♪]

23:43.172 --> 23:44.548
Be safe.

23:56.977 --> 23:59.146
[♪♪♪]

23:59.146 --> 24:01.274
Bill.

24:01.274 --> 24:02.900
This just came
from Headquarters.

24:02.900 --> 24:04.110
News on the Tates?

24:04.110 --> 24:05.652
News on Henry Gowen.

24:05.652 --> 24:07.947
The Inspector General
just found a bank employee,

24:07.947 --> 24:10.074
a forensic accountant,
who's willing to testify

24:10.074 --> 24:12.076
that Gowen embezzled
the town's money.

24:12.076 --> 24:13.619
The problem with sin

24:13.619 --> 24:15.495
is that
it rarely stays private.

24:15.495 --> 24:19.125
They gave this A.J. Foster
fellow immunity to talk.

24:19.125 --> 24:21.877
Says he was paid
to cover the paper trail.

24:21.877 --> 24:23.712
So when
can you arrest Gowen?

24:23.712 --> 24:25.131
It's not that simple.

24:25.131 --> 24:26.924
The evidence has to be
put before the court,

24:26.924 --> 24:28.592
and I can't do anything
until the judge

24:28.592 --> 24:29.676
signs off on a warrant.

24:29.676 --> 24:30.844
How long's that take?

24:30.844 --> 24:31.971
Depends on the judge.

24:31.971 --> 24:34.056
Weeks...
maybe months.

24:34.056 --> 24:36.350
Doesn't seem right,
him being able to roam free.

24:36.350 --> 24:37.643
Gowen's slick.

24:37.643 --> 24:39.312
This has been coming
for a while.

24:39.312 --> 24:40.854
It's only a matter of time.

24:43.649 --> 24:45.318
Hyah.

24:46.652 --> 24:47.778
Hyah!

24:52.574 --> 24:54.034
Bye.

24:54.034 --> 24:55.286
[SIGHS]

24:57.246 --> 24:59.581
Well, this is it.

24:59.581 --> 25:01.499
The Hope Valley Infirmary.

25:01.499 --> 25:03.002
I'm impressed.

25:03.002 --> 25:05.129
There's really not
much to see, yet.

25:05.129 --> 25:06.297
Slowly, but surely.

25:06.297 --> 25:07.881
I think
you're doing a great job,

25:07.881 --> 25:09.342
and I hear you've been busy.

25:09.342 --> 25:11.385
Busier every week,
but nothing I can't handle.

25:11.385 --> 25:12.719
I know
I've said this before,

25:12.719 --> 25:14.138
but we are lucky to have you.

25:14.138 --> 25:15.722
And it looks like
you've done a lot

25:15.722 --> 25:17.099
with what we gave you.

25:17.099 --> 25:20.269
The railroad's
been very generous.

25:20.269 --> 25:22.146
You sound surprised.

25:22.146 --> 25:24.273
You probably know
National Pacific doesn't have

25:24.273 --> 25:25.899
a very good reputation
when it comes

25:25.899 --> 25:27.485
to looking after people.
[SIGHS]

25:27.485 --> 25:29.278
That is all in the past.

25:29.278 --> 25:31.238
I'm here to prove them wrong.

25:31.238 --> 25:32.906
Believe it or not,
the railroad cares

25:32.906 --> 25:34.408
about doing the right thing,

25:34.408 --> 25:36.952
for our communities
and for mankind.

25:36.952 --> 25:38.329
And womankind?

25:38.329 --> 25:39.579
Well, womankind has always

25:39.579 --> 25:40.956
been a particular
favorite of mine,

25:40.956 --> 25:42.582
but that's a story
for another day.

25:42.582 --> 25:44.251
[KNOCK ON DOOR]

25:44.251 --> 25:45.669
Nurse Carter?

25:45.669 --> 25:47.129
Oh, another patient.

25:47.129 --> 25:48.506
I'll leave you to it.

25:48.506 --> 25:49.965
Yes. Right here.

25:49.965 --> 25:51.758
We think
it's just a sprain,

25:51.758 --> 25:53.511
but thought you'd
better take a look.

25:53.511 --> 25:54.887
How did it happen?

25:54.887 --> 25:56.680
He twisted it,
working on the green chain.

25:56.680 --> 25:57.931
Nobody's fault.

25:57.931 --> 25:59.475
Just got careless,
that's all.

25:59.475 --> 26:01.394
A sawmill's not
a good place for carelessness.

26:01.394 --> 26:04.021
Well, everybody's working some
pretty long hours these days.

26:04.021 --> 26:07.274
Tired people make mistakes,
and mistakes get people hurt.

26:07.274 --> 26:09.735
I've seen too many
of your men in here lately.

26:09.735 --> 26:10.903
What can I tell you?

26:10.903 --> 26:12.363
We've got
a lot of orders to fill.

26:12.363 --> 26:13.906
We're running at full capacity.

26:13.906 --> 26:16.242
You could tell Mr. Coulter
his men need a break.

26:16.242 --> 26:18.994
Sorry, ma'am, but I don't
tell my boss what to do.

26:21.080 --> 26:22.622
[DOOR OPENS, CLOSES]

26:22.622 --> 26:24.124
[PATIENT GROANS]
It's okay.

26:26.626 --> 26:28.962
TATE:
Do you think you can
you hit 'em from here?

26:28.962 --> 26:30.381
Sure.

26:30.381 --> 26:32.299
Easy shot.

26:34.009 --> 26:36.262
You miss,
you don't get paid.

26:37.471 --> 26:39.181
I don't miss.

26:39.181 --> 26:40.891
Good.

26:40.891 --> 26:42.435
We'll be down
in that gully,

26:42.435 --> 26:43.436
out of sight.

26:43.436 --> 26:44.895
As soon as you fire,

26:44.895 --> 26:46.897
we'll take the wagon.

26:46.897 --> 26:48.982
You sure you want them dead?

26:50.276 --> 26:51.735
That a problem?

26:53.028 --> 26:54.654
Not for me.

26:54.654 --> 26:56.656
[♪♪♪]

26:58.325 --> 27:00.286
Eight men have been hurt
this week alone.

27:00.286 --> 27:02.329
Maybe I should speak
to Mr. Coulter.

27:02.329 --> 27:03.747
I've already
talked to him.

27:03.747 --> 27:05.040
He's under
a lot of pressure

27:05.040 --> 27:06.875
to deliver
Mr. Wyatt's order on time.

27:06.875 --> 27:08.794
Then maybe someone
should talk to Mr. Wyatt.

27:08.794 --> 27:11.213
Raffle tickets,
only five cents!

27:11.213 --> 27:12.839
ELIZABETH:
How many have you sold?

27:12.839 --> 27:13.882
Two.

27:13.882 --> 27:15.301
Only two?

27:15.301 --> 27:16.802
Well, then,
I'll take 10.

27:16.802 --> 27:19.096
Fifty cents
for the book of 10.

27:19.096 --> 27:20.473
I'll take
two dozen.

27:20.473 --> 27:21.599
How many's that?

27:21.599 --> 27:23.934
WYATT:
Twenty-four. You know what?

27:23.934 --> 27:26.145
You might as well make it
an even 30.

27:26.145 --> 27:27.271
Thanks, mister.

27:27.271 --> 27:29.356
Here you go.
Keep the change.

27:29.356 --> 27:31.733
That is very generous
of you, Mr. Wyatt.

27:31.733 --> 27:33.860
Always happy
to support the community.

27:33.860 --> 27:36.113
Um, speaking of that,

27:36.113 --> 27:38.740
I was hoping to talk to you
about something important.

27:38.740 --> 27:39.825
Of course.

27:39.825 --> 27:41.118
It's the sawmill.

27:41.118 --> 27:42.786
Now, I know you have
a signed contract

27:42.786 --> 27:43.996
with Mr. Coulter, but...

27:43.996 --> 27:46.706
the deadline
you've given him is...

27:47.625 --> 27:50.252
Well, it's unreasonable.

27:50.252 --> 27:51.587
"Unreasonable?"

27:51.587 --> 27:54.047
What Miss Thatcher
means to say

27:54.047 --> 27:56.133
is that the men
at the mill

27:56.133 --> 27:57.510
have been
working so hard,

27:57.510 --> 27:58.927
that they're getting hurt.

27:58.927 --> 28:00.638
I'm seeing a lot of them
at the infirmary,

28:00.638 --> 28:02.431
I'm sure you wouldn't
want that to happen.

28:02.431 --> 28:03.849
No, no. Of course not.

28:03.849 --> 28:05.601
ELIZABETH:
So If you could
just extend

28:05.601 --> 28:06.810
the delivery deadline,

28:06.810 --> 28:08.270
it would really
make a difference.

28:08.270 --> 28:09.605
And the workers
could rest,

28:09.605 --> 28:11.148
and spend time
with their families.

28:11.148 --> 28:13.233
I appreciate your concern,
Miss Thatcher,

28:13.233 --> 28:15.027
but I have a business to run.

28:15.027 --> 28:19.031
How the men spend their time
is not really my concern.

28:19.031 --> 28:20.698
[SIGHS]

28:20.698 --> 28:22.826
Could you
please reconsider?

28:22.826 --> 28:25.120
It would mean
so much to everyone.

28:25.120 --> 28:26.413
There's gonna be
a carnival

28:26.413 --> 28:28.165
to raise money
for the school.

28:28.165 --> 28:30.876
Wouldn't it be nice if
the fathers could come too?

28:30.876 --> 28:32.252
[SCOFFS]

28:32.252 --> 28:35.422
I suppose an extra day
won't hurt anything.

28:35.422 --> 28:37.633
Will you
be at the carnival?

28:37.633 --> 28:39.009
I wouldn't miss it.

28:39.009 --> 28:41.303
Then I'll see you there.

28:42.513 --> 28:44.056
[GASP]

28:44.056 --> 28:45.182
Heh.

28:46.183 --> 28:48.143
Oh, excuse me.

28:48.143 --> 28:49.562
Mr. Cantrell!!

28:49.562 --> 28:50.729
Mr. Cantrell!.

28:50.729 --> 28:52.981
I have good news.

28:52.981 --> 28:55.275
The delivery deadline
has been extended.

28:55.275 --> 28:57.110
Oh? I hadn't heard.

28:57.110 --> 28:58.696
I'm not sure,
but I think that

28:58.696 --> 29:00.906
means Mr. Coulter might
give you the afternoon off

29:00.906 --> 29:03.701
so you could take Philip
to the carnival.

29:03.701 --> 29:05.369
I can't afford
to take time off.

29:05.369 --> 29:06.953
Well, it's just
a few hours.

29:06.953 --> 29:09.665
Maybe to you,
but it's money in my pocket.

29:09.665 --> 29:10.999
Please?

29:10.999 --> 29:12.585
Philip only gets
one childhood,

29:12.585 --> 29:14.628
and you don't
get to go back and do it over.

29:15.629 --> 29:17.464
I have to get back
to the mill.

29:17.464 --> 29:18.674
Excuse me.

29:20.467 --> 29:21.468
[SIGH]

29:21.468 --> 29:23.512
Any sign of Frank?

29:23.512 --> 29:25.556
I spotted him flanking us
a while back.

29:25.556 --> 29:27.641
He's done a good job
of staying out of sight.

29:27.641 --> 29:29.893
Pastor's not
short on courage,

29:29.893 --> 29:31.228
I'll give him that.

29:31.228 --> 29:32.938
As long as he doesn't
try any heroics,

29:32.938 --> 29:34.356
he should be fine.

29:34.356 --> 29:36.525
He's not the one
I'm worried about.

29:41.447 --> 29:43.240
[WAGON RUMBLING DISTANTLY]

29:44.742 --> 29:47.119
[♪♪♪]

30:04.094 --> 30:05.178
[GRUNTS]

30:06.221 --> 30:07.514
[HORSES NEIGH]

30:08.307 --> 30:09.808
That was
only one shot.

30:09.808 --> 30:11.059
Maybe he missed.

30:11.059 --> 30:12.352
We better
clear out of here.

30:12.352 --> 30:13.687
[HORSE NEIGHS]

30:14.813 --> 30:16.398
[BOTH GRUNT]

30:25.491 --> 30:27.618
[♪♪♪]

30:30.996 --> 30:32.247
Bill tells me
you took down

30:32.247 --> 30:33.832
that sharpshooter
all by yourself.

30:33.832 --> 30:35.334
FRANK:
It's no big deal.

30:35.334 --> 30:37.085
WYATT:
You are a man
of many talents, Pastor.

30:37.085 --> 30:39.212
Let me show you
my gratitude.

30:39.212 --> 30:41.381
I appreciate it,
but I don't need a reward

30:41.381 --> 30:42.882
for doing a good deed,
thanks.

30:42.882 --> 30:44.968
Going up against a rifle
with your bare hands

30:44.968 --> 30:46.386
is more than a good deed.

30:46.386 --> 30:48.388
FRANK:
I had a pleasant ride
with my friends,

30:48.388 --> 30:49.682
got a little exercise.

30:49.682 --> 30:51.517
I won't take
your money for that.

30:51.517 --> 30:52.934
Okay. but don't be surprised

30:52.934 --> 30:54.853
if your collection plate
is fuller than usual

30:54.853 --> 30:56.355
this Sunday.
And you're gonna see

30:56.355 --> 30:58.106
a nice little bonus
in your pay this week.

30:58.106 --> 31:00.442
I have no problem
taking your money.

31:00.442 --> 31:02.695
I didn't know Frank
rode with Bill and Jack

31:02.695 --> 31:03.945
to guard the stage.

31:03.945 --> 31:05.489
Neither did I.

31:05.489 --> 31:07.324
Our sharpshooter
isn't talking.

31:07.324 --> 31:09.117
Hired guns usually
don't, Jack.

31:09.117 --> 31:11.161
I bet he'll have something
to say to the judge.

31:11.161 --> 31:12.996
In the meantime,
he can enjoy the comforts

31:12.996 --> 31:14.331
of his jail cell.

31:17.125 --> 31:18.377
Excuse me.

31:24.717 --> 31:26.885
I told you I'd be back
by nightfall.

31:29.929 --> 31:31.973
[♪♪♪]

31:34.976 --> 31:36.478
Abigail!

31:38.605 --> 31:40.524
What's wrong?

31:40.524 --> 31:42.942
You rode out of town
on a dangerous job

31:42.942 --> 31:44.820
without even
telling me. Why?

31:44.820 --> 31:46.196
It wasn't that dangerous.

31:46.196 --> 31:47.906
Ray Wyatt disagrees.

31:47.906 --> 31:49.616
Should I have
asked for permission?

31:49.616 --> 31:51.493
Frank, it's not
about permission.

31:51.493 --> 31:53.328
I can't tell you
what to do.

31:53.328 --> 31:55.330
I'm just trying
to understand you.

31:55.330 --> 31:57.040
You say you've put
your past behind you,

31:57.040 --> 31:58.124
and then,
out of the blue,

31:58.124 --> 31:59.251
you go and chase outlaws.

31:59.251 --> 32:00.252
They needed my help.

32:00.252 --> 32:01.211
I don't see the problem.

32:01.211 --> 32:02.254
The problem is,

32:02.254 --> 32:03.630
I would like us to be close.

32:03.630 --> 32:05.424
To communicate,
to be honest.

32:05.424 --> 32:07.300
So now I'm not honest?

32:07.300 --> 32:08.594
I didn't say that.

32:08.594 --> 32:10.387
I guess we're not
communicating.

32:11.555 --> 32:13.599
Maybe we should
give it a rest.

32:14.892 --> 32:16.685
Maybe we should.

32:23.901 --> 32:25.694
[CRICKETS CHIRPING]

32:25.694 --> 32:28.196
ELIZABETH:
How's the sign
for the photo booth coming?

32:28.196 --> 32:29.656
JACK:
Almost done.

32:30.866 --> 32:32.659
What do you think
so far?

32:33.744 --> 32:35.746
It is a work of art.

32:35.746 --> 32:37.289
Well, in that case,

32:37.289 --> 32:39.207
maybe I should charge
10 cents.
[GIGGLES]

32:39.207 --> 32:41.376
Did you buy
your raffle ticket yet?

32:41.376 --> 32:43.670
Actually, I bought
20 raffle tickets,

32:43.670 --> 32:45.505
and if I win
that hair comb,

32:45.505 --> 32:47.173
I'm giving it
straight to you.

32:47.173 --> 32:48.133
[CHUCKLES]

32:48.133 --> 32:49.259
[DOOR KNOCKS]

32:49.259 --> 32:51.177
Yoo-hoo!

32:51.177 --> 32:52.429
[SIGHS]
Maybe we should

32:52.429 --> 32:53.722
start locking the door.

32:53.722 --> 32:55.766
Lee has exciting news!

32:55.766 --> 32:57.684
Is it about Mr. Wyatt
extending the deadline?

32:57.684 --> 33:00.646
Oh, dear. These walls
truly are thin.

33:00.646 --> 33:02.481
Wyatt said that
you and Faith Carter

33:02.481 --> 33:03.732
convinced him to do it.

33:03.732 --> 33:05.567
Well, Faith did
most of the convincing.

33:05.567 --> 33:07.778
And I did
some convincing too.

33:07.778 --> 33:09.321
Let's not forget that.
Mm-hmm.

33:09.321 --> 33:11.615
So you're closing down
for the afternoon?

33:11.615 --> 33:13.617
Pretty much, yeah.
A few of the guys

33:13.617 --> 33:15.327
really wanted
to keep working, so I'm, uh,

33:15.327 --> 33:16.662
I'm paying
them double-time.

33:16.662 --> 33:18.622
That is very
generous of you, Lee.

33:18.622 --> 33:21.374
Thank you so much, Lee.
The students will be so happy.

33:22.501 --> 33:23.877
Ah, what can I say?

33:23.877 --> 33:25.712
[♪♪♪]

33:25.712 --> 33:29.174
Dad, can we get candy apples
at the carnival?

33:30.175 --> 33:32.051
You know
I have to work.

33:32.051 --> 33:35.305
But the sawmill's closed
tomorrow afternoon.

33:35.305 --> 33:36.890
Not for everybody.

33:36.890 --> 33:38.809
It gives me a chance
to make some extra money,

33:38.809 --> 33:40.894
get us out of
this tent sooner.

33:40.894 --> 33:42.855
I don't mind this tent.

33:43.981 --> 33:45.858
You need a real bed.

33:45.858 --> 33:47.442
I'm doing what's best, son.

33:47.442 --> 33:49.235
You'll understand
when you're older.

33:49.235 --> 33:50.779
Yes, sir.

33:52.781 --> 33:55.241
You're gonna be all right
without me there, aren't you?

33:55.868 --> 33:56.952
Sure.

33:58.244 --> 34:00.914
Carnival's not
so much fun anyways.

34:08.171 --> 34:09.756
WOMAN:
Oh, we're so close!

34:09.756 --> 34:11.884
[♪♪♪]

34:11.884 --> 34:14.427
[WOMAN CHEERS]
[PEOPLE TALKING INDISTINCTLY]

34:18.598 --> 34:20.266
You two
make a lovely couple.

34:20.266 --> 34:22.019
Care for a photograph?

34:27.900 --> 34:29.317
[YELLING]
Cupcakes!

34:29.317 --> 34:31.403
Get your fresh-baked
cupcakes right here!

34:31.403 --> 34:32.905
Cupcakes!

34:32.905 --> 34:33.989
Cupcakes!

34:33.989 --> 34:35.699
Do you have to yell?

34:35.699 --> 34:37.701
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
Don't you wanna make
some money?

34:37.701 --> 34:39.661
Cody, you could be
a little quieter.

34:39.661 --> 34:40.662
[CHUCKLES]

34:40.662 --> 34:41.955
Cupcakes for sale.

34:41.955 --> 34:43.540
Get 'em before
they're gone.

34:43.540 --> 34:45.042
I'll take a couple.

34:45.042 --> 34:46.793
Oh, see?
You don't have to shout.

34:46.793 --> 34:48.003
[COINS RATTLE]

34:48.003 --> 34:50.005
[♪♪♪]

34:54.676 --> 34:56.595
Oh! What are you
gonna have?

34:58.013 --> 35:00.265
You look lovely,
take a photograph.

35:02.141 --> 35:03.727
[LAUGHS SOFTLY]

35:03.727 --> 35:06.145
[♪♪♪]

35:08.023 --> 35:09.649
Can you tell me my future?

35:09.649 --> 35:11.568
[WITH ACCENT]
Of course I can!

35:11.568 --> 35:13.987
I have a third eye

35:13.987 --> 35:18.450
that can see
and hear everything.

35:18.450 --> 35:20.077
An eye that hears?

35:20.077 --> 35:22.287
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
Well, it could hear
a lot better

35:22.287 --> 35:25.040
if you would settle down
and stop your chattering.

35:25.040 --> 35:27.166
[WITH ACCENT]
I see...

35:27.166 --> 35:28.835
true love

35:28.835 --> 35:30.754
in your future.

35:30.754 --> 35:32.547
A tall, dark, handsome man?

35:32.547 --> 35:33.632
No.

35:33.632 --> 35:34.758
[GASPS]

35:34.758 --> 35:35.759
Hideous!

35:35.759 --> 35:37.719
But you will love him

35:37.719 --> 35:40.221
nonetheless.

35:40.221 --> 35:42.641
Because he'll be a good man?

35:42.641 --> 35:45.351
Because he will be rich.

35:45.351 --> 35:47.437
And you will be very happy.

35:48.354 --> 35:49.689
[COINS RATTLE]

35:51.524 --> 35:54.027
But he'll be hideous?

35:54.027 --> 35:55.988
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
I'm teasing.

35:55.988 --> 35:57.823
He'll be very handsome.

35:57.823 --> 35:58.824
[COINS RATTLE]

35:58.824 --> 35:59.866
Ten cents, please.

35:59.866 --> 36:01.326
[COINS CLATTER]

36:01.326 --> 36:02.661
Thank you.

36:02.661 --> 36:04.537
DOTTIE:
My turn.

36:04.537 --> 36:06.665
[WITH ACCENT]
Please.

36:06.665 --> 36:08.041
I see...

36:08.041 --> 36:11.920
great success
with your dress shop.

36:11.920 --> 36:13.880
That is...

36:13.880 --> 36:16.091
if you have the wisdom

36:16.091 --> 36:18.927
to choose a talented

36:18.927 --> 36:21.513
fashion designer

36:21.513 --> 36:24.349
to assist you.

36:24.349 --> 36:26.935
I don't suppose
you've got your third eye

36:26.935 --> 36:29.062
on anyone in particular?

36:31.314 --> 36:33.399
[IN NORMAL VOICE]
Funny, that...

36:33.399 --> 36:34.484
Hmm.

36:35.568 --> 36:36.736
[SIGHS]

36:36.736 --> 36:37.779
[COINS RATTLE]

36:37.779 --> 36:39.156
Oh.

36:39.156 --> 36:40.490
[COIN DROPS]

36:46.038 --> 36:48.623
[♪♪♪]

36:49.916 --> 36:51.584
Don't seem to be
doing much business.

36:52.627 --> 36:53.962
Maybe you'd like
to buy a ticket.

36:53.962 --> 36:56.255
I'd like to buy
all your tickets.

36:57.799 --> 36:59.551
Wonderful!

36:59.551 --> 37:02.428
You are making
a generous contribution

37:02.428 --> 37:03.847
to Hope Valley's
future.

37:05.473 --> 37:06.641
Shall we?

37:06.641 --> 37:07.642
Oh...

37:07.642 --> 37:09.019
I'm just doing the selling.

37:09.019 --> 37:11.063
Florence is doing the kissing.

37:12.522 --> 37:14.315
[LAUGHS]

37:17.360 --> 37:20.697
All right, folks, last call
for the three-legged race!

37:20.697 --> 37:22.281
[APPLAUDING]

37:22.281 --> 37:23.324
Your father
had to work?

37:23.324 --> 37:24.826
Yeah.

37:24.826 --> 37:26.828
Oh, Philip, I'm so sorry.

37:28.287 --> 37:30.665
[♪♪♪]

37:30.665 --> 37:32.291
Would you like to race?

37:32.291 --> 37:33.793
I'm in need of a partner.

37:33.793 --> 37:34.961
Is that allowed?

37:34.961 --> 37:36.671
Of course! Come on.

37:36.671 --> 37:37.923
Okay.

37:37.923 --> 37:39.424
One more team!
Okay.

37:39.424 --> 37:41.300
All right.
Here we go!

37:41.300 --> 37:43.302
All right.
Tie you up here.

37:43.302 --> 37:45.346
Nice and tight.
Thank you, Bill.

37:45.346 --> 37:47.057
Oh, my goodness.

37:47.057 --> 37:48.600
It's been years since
I've done this.

37:48.600 --> 37:49.976
Can't believe
we're doing this.

37:49.976 --> 37:51.519
All right, everybody.

37:52.771 --> 37:54.397
Ready?

37:54.397 --> 37:56.441
Set...

37:56.441 --> 37:57.525
Go!

37:57.525 --> 37:58.818
LEE:
And they're off!

37:58.818 --> 38:00.445
In the lead,
it's Jack and Robert,

38:00.445 --> 38:03.489
No! On the ground,
it's Jack and Robert.

38:03.489 --> 38:05.867
And it's Elizabeth and Philip
who've taken the lead!

38:05.867 --> 38:08.453
And Abigail and Cody
are gaining real fast!

38:08.453 --> 38:11.164
It's coming to the wire!
Too close to call! It's--

38:12.958 --> 38:15.543
Elizabeth and Philip
by a finger!

38:15.543 --> 38:17.837
[CHEERING]

38:17.837 --> 38:19.464
[WHISTLES]

38:20.590 --> 38:22.175
Daddy! You came!

38:22.175 --> 38:24.552
Figured working a half-shift
was enough for today.

38:24.552 --> 38:26.304
Too late?

38:26.304 --> 38:28.140
It's never too late.

38:30.225 --> 38:32.227
Now, where are
those candy apples?

38:32.227 --> 38:33.352
This way!

38:34.896 --> 38:36.397
[CHUCKLES]

38:39.943 --> 38:42.528
[♪♪♪]

38:44.156 --> 38:46.616
Did you enjoy
yourself, Mr. Wyatt?

38:46.616 --> 38:47.700
More than I expected.

38:47.700 --> 38:49.161
[CHUCKLES]

38:49.161 --> 38:51.955
I know this isn't a day
to discuss business,

38:51.955 --> 38:53.873
but I wonder if you've
considered our request

38:53.873 --> 38:55.750
to waive
the railroad's taxes?

38:55.750 --> 38:56.960
Actually, yes.

38:56.960 --> 38:58.003
I've done some homework,

38:58.003 --> 38:59.712
and I found out
that most cities

38:59.712 --> 39:01.256
that do business
with the railroad

39:01.256 --> 39:02.841
offer a small
tax reduction,

39:02.841 --> 39:04.676
but nothing more.

39:04.676 --> 39:08.013
So I'm thinking I'll reduce
your taxes by 20 percent.

39:08.013 --> 39:11.057
But-- You're right,
of course.

39:11.057 --> 39:12.892
This is not the day
to discuss business.

39:12.892 --> 39:15.020
Enjoy your afternoon,
and...

39:15.020 --> 39:16.521
You missed a spot.

39:16.521 --> 39:18.857
[♪♪♪]

39:20.483 --> 39:21.985
Mr. Wyatt.

39:21.985 --> 39:23.695
Mr. Gowen.

39:25.697 --> 39:28.992
So how are you getting on
with Madam Mayor?

39:28.992 --> 39:32.495
Or as you called her,
the "Little Lady"?

39:32.495 --> 39:33.663
Not well.

39:35.456 --> 39:38.710
Hope Valley seems to have
quite a few headstrong women.

39:38.710 --> 39:40.086
Well, that's fair to say.

39:40.086 --> 39:41.796
Perhaps
we'd find it easier

39:41.796 --> 39:43.840
dealing with
a more reasonable man.

39:44.799 --> 39:46.259
Perhaps.

39:47.426 --> 39:49.346
Shall we discuss it
in my office?

39:49.346 --> 39:50.847
Let's.

39:50.847 --> 39:53.474
[♪♪♪]

39:57.645 --> 39:59.397
Think Floyd'll talk?

39:59.397 --> 40:01.107
[FIRE CRACKLING]

40:01.107 --> 40:02.567
Doesn't matter.

40:02.567 --> 40:04.443
The Mounties
haven't found us yet.

40:04.443 --> 40:06.029
They will if we can't
get enough money

40:06.029 --> 40:07.906
to make it
across the border.

40:07.906 --> 40:10.449
We'll find another way to get
our hands on that payroll.

40:14.579 --> 40:17.749
So? How much money
did you raise?

40:17.749 --> 40:19.751
Enough to buy
brand-new readers

40:19.751 --> 40:21.794
for the entire class,
and then some.

40:23.338 --> 40:24.964
Then you should
be happy.

40:24.964 --> 40:27.508
There's just so much more
the classroom still needs.

40:27.508 --> 40:30.303
Maps, art supplies,
musical instruments...

40:30.303 --> 40:31.971
and I can't exactly
put on a carnival

40:31.971 --> 40:33.765
every time I'm running
short of something.

40:33.765 --> 40:35.767
Those are
tomorrow's problems.

40:35.767 --> 40:37.643
Look at what
you did today.

40:37.643 --> 40:39.478
Well, it's not that
much of a challenge

40:39.478 --> 40:41.314
to oversee a few
games and races.

40:41.314 --> 40:43.191
Oh, it was more than that.

40:43.191 --> 40:45.610
You gave the town
a day of fun,

40:45.610 --> 40:47.737
and you brought
a father and son together.

40:47.737 --> 40:49.322
Shane and Philip?

40:49.322 --> 40:51.116
I'm really glad
Shane showed up,

40:51.116 --> 40:52.909
but they still have
a long way to go.

40:52.909 --> 40:54.660
You helped them
take the first step.

40:54.660 --> 40:56.495
I'd call that
a good start.

40:58.748 --> 41:01.584
You do so much
for this town, Elizabeth.

41:01.584 --> 41:04.545
I don't know where Hope Valley
would be without you.

41:05.838 --> 41:07.257
Well...

41:07.257 --> 41:09.592
if you really
feel that way, Constable...

41:10.760 --> 41:12.387
Then I guess I could
stick around

41:12.387 --> 41:13.512
for a while.

41:19.352 --> 41:22.439
[♪♪♪]

41:27.235 --> 41:29.862
[♪♪♪]
